SYPHILIS - USA (08): (PENNSYLVANIA) RISING INCIDENCE, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*****************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 28 Apr 2015
Source: Erie Times-News [edited]
http://www.goerie.com/erie-county-sees-spike-in-syphilis-cases


During the 1st 3 months of 2015, 20 cases [of syphilis] were reported to the Erie County [in the US state of Pennsylvania] Department of Health, said Charlotte Berringer, RN, director of community health for the Erie County Department of Health.

It's the most cases reported during a 3-month period since at least 1995 and more than any full year during that time except for 2014, when 22 cases were reported.

"It is a significant concern," said Berringer, who has issued a health advisory to county health-care providers about syphilis. "Syphilis is a disease that comes in waves and that's what is happening. Until recently, we were seeing between zero and 5 cases a year."

Berringer shared information and statistics about syphilis during Monday's [27 Apr 2015] Erie County Board of Health meeting. Erie County sees far fewer cases of syphilis than it does other sexually transmitted diseases [STDs] like chlamydia and gonorrhea, but syphilis is a concern because it can lead to paralysis, blindness, dementia, and death if left untreated. Most people with syphilis can be easily treated with antibiotics in the disease's early stages.

Adagio Health, Community Health Net, and the Health Department all provide free and confidential STD testing. Patients also can visit their family physician, Berringer said.

[Byline: David Bruce]

